One important trick is that one doesn‚Äôt need to optimize one weight per frame, but instead can optimize one Lagrange multiplier per measurement. This is typically a much smaller number. The two are mathematically equivalent (under the assumptions we use). 6/

In practice this is done by building a free-energy like function F=chi2-Theta*S, where chi2 acts as an enthalpy and the KL-divergence as an entropy. The ‚ÄúTemperature‚Äù, Theta, tunes the balance between these terms. 5/
James from Team Rocket and I have the exact same trans energy https://t.co/DVT2Wxiva6

In short, the method aims to reweight each frame in a trajectory to (i) improve agreement with experiment and (ii) stay as close as possible to the (force field) prior. The first is encoded in a chi2-term and the second in an cross-entropy term (KL-divergence to prior) 4/

Fundamentally, this is a very simple approach that doesn‚Äôt require biasing the MD/MC trajectory, and where it is easy to play around using different kinds and amounts of data. It‚Äôs also relatively fast once you have the simulation. We aimed for simplicity. 3/

The software implements a Bayesian/Maximum Entropy approach to reweight a molecular simulation to improve agreement with experimental data. The approach is similar to that of others (Hummer, Bussi, ‚Ä¶; see refs)  2/ https://t.co/5xgsiu96io

The importance of Wolbachia is established and is being exploited as a drug target by @AWOL_Wolbachia . However, there is still much to learn about the intimate relationship between the worm and its bacterial symbiont.
The differences across life stages do identify some interesting questions surrounding how Wolbachia density is regulated, and what the mutualistic relationship truly is.

Considering the microfilaria dying in the skin are the major immunological target, and there is very little variation in Wolbachia copy number been microfilariae individuals, it seems further unlikely that Wolbachia density drives pathology variation.

SO.... this paper examines the Wolbachia density across microfilaria, L1, iL3, adult male and female life stages. Very little variation was found between samples from the immature stages, whereas the adult stages were highly variable.

HOWEVER... Sam showed in a much larger cohort sampled across a much larger range in Ghana that Wolbachia copy number per worm is extremely variable, and that the forest/savannah Wolbachia correlation did not hold. https://t.co/zt5MNtN3zk

One study identified a correlation between Wolbachia density and ecotype, with higher Wolbachia copy number in the savannah relative to the forest form. This sounds sensible - if Wolbachia are immunoreactive, MORE Wolbachia would be more immunoreactive, causing greater disease

For a long time, two "ecotypes" of O. volvulus have been described (of course, an oversimplification for many reasons, but that is not for now) - a forest form and a savannah form, with the latter causing much more disease.

The hypothesis is that worms (predominantly microfilaria) die in the skin, Wolbachia proteins are released, and the body reacts to this. Thus, it is not the worm itself, but the Wolbachia within, that causes disease.

There is an intriguing backstory to this work. Wolbachia are important intracellular symbionts of a number of filarial nematodes. A number of studies have made the link between the immunoreactivity of Wolbachia proteins and the disease presentation of onchocerciasis.
